---------------------------------------------------------------------------
WORLD ROUND-UP
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: WikiLeaks: campuses ideological battlegrounds

Diplomatic cables recently made public by the WikiLeaks website show how
the United States and other nations have focused on colleges and
universities as key battlegrounds in their efforts to win over hearts and
minds, writes Peter Schmidt for The Chronicle of Higher Education.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214644219

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Columbia reverses anti-WikiLeaks guidance

Days after Columbia University=92s School of International and Public
Affairs, SIPA, caused an uproar by warning its students against linking to
WikiLeaks or discussing the secret-spilling website=92s latest cache of
diplomatic cables online, the prestigious training ground for future
diplomats has changed tack and embraced free speech, writes Sam Gustin for
Wired.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101211211502774

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: Top test scores from Shanghai stun educators

With China=92s debut in international standardised testing, students in
Shanghai have surprised experts by outscoring their counterparts in dozens
of other countries, in reading as well as in maths and science, according
to the results of a respected exam, writes Sam Dillon for The New York
Times.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010121021455746

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Third of universities in England could close

More than a third of England=92s universities may be forced to close or mer=
ge
as a result of swingeing public cuts to higher education, an analysis by
the lecturers=92 trade union has found, writes Jessica Shepherd for the
Guardian.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101211211702791

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SUDAN: Ministry repatriates colleges from north

Sudan=92s Ministry for Higher Education, Research, Science and Technology
finally launched last Monday the relocation of Southern Sudan University
colleges operating in the north in a repatriation scheme that ends in five
days, writes Mabior Philip for Borglobe.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101211211806791

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

QATAR: Educators from across world talk about change

Over 1,200 people who work in education across the world arrived last week
in the small, oil-wealthy Persian Gulf emirate of Qatar, writes Ursula
Lindsey for The Chronicle of Higher Education. The visitors, scattered
across Doha=92s five-star hotels and attended to by squadrons of PR people,
were there for the second World Innovation Summit for Education, more
commonly known as WISE, which bills itself as =93building the future of
education=94.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214507660

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CANADA: Canadian outlawed from top US stem cell post

In the global endeavour that science has become, where research knows no
borders, it is a strange story, writes Carolyn Abraham for the Globe and
Mail. An internationally respected Canadian scientist who was the leading
candidate to become the head of California=92s high-profile stem cell
research institute was, at the last minute, banned from consideration
because he is not an American.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010121021441927

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

TAIWAN: Asia=92s first US-accredited university

Taiwan=92s Ming Chuan University, MCU, has received accreditation from the
Middle States Commission on Higher Education to become the first university
in Asia to be accredited in the US education system, the university=92s
President Lee Chuan said at a press conference in Taipei, reports The China
Post.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101211212031405

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDIA-FRANCE: Two higher education agreements signed

India and France on Monday signed two memorandums of understanding on
higher education, and also decided to take forward a 2009 Plan of Action
for the Indian Institute of Technology-Rajasthan by setting up a French
consortium that will help the institute gain expertise in areas like health
technology, solar energy, aerospace, quantum computing and several other
fields, reports The Times of India.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101211212131466

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SOUTH KOREA: Top university given world-class boost

Seoul National University has been given a weighty opportunity to boost its
competitiveness in the world as a result of the passage on Wednesday in the
national assembly of a bill on the establishment and management of the
prestigious institution, comments the Korea Joongang Daily. The bill=92s
passage was welcome after irksome meandering on the issue for more than two
decades.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214333968

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

JAPAN: Firms turning to foreign students

University students are having a hard time finding jobs amid the economic
downturn, with those who have secured employment starting after their
scheduled graduation next spring hitting a record low of 57.6% in October,
reports Kyodo News. But a new trend among firms to seek more aggressive and
proactive employees may be creating more chances for foreign students
seeking work experience in Japan, even in the increasingly competitive job
market.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214247265

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDONESIA: Graduates struggle to find jobs

University and diploma graduates in Indonesia find it harder to secure a
job than high school graduates, the latest Central Statistics Agency report
reveals, reports The Jakarta Post.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214207187

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Report on commercial colleges revised

After reviewing 80 hours of videotapes by its undercover investigators, to
remove personally identifiable information, the US Government
Accountability Office has revised its hard-hitting report on recruiting
practices in for-profit higher education =96 softening some of the findings
but without changing its conclusion that the colleges visited had engaged
in deception or fraud =96 writes Tamar Lewin for The New York Times.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101211211918846

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Sabbaticals under fire at Minnesota universities

Of the 3,340 full-time and 760 part-time faculty members in the University
of Minnesota system, 104 went on sabbatical and 83 went on semester leave
from 2009-10, writes Adam Daniels for The Minnesota Daily. But with looming
budget problems crippling public universities across the country, lawmakers
are looking at cutting sabbaticals as a way to balance the books.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214045139

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Public blames graduation rates on students

The public pins most of the blame for poor college graduation rates on
students and their parents and gives a pass to colleges, government
officials and others, a new Associated Press-Stanford University poll
shows, reports Associated Press.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101210214012174


